Mansour was born in Monrovia, but has been living in the U.S. for the last five years, in Lakewood, Calif. Mansour has joined other students from Cormier’s Foundation for Improved Living in the Ndaba region, building wells, raising money for education and digging for gold and rubies, he said.

Staying in a simple scene: a family’s compound, made of dirt floors and a tin roof, pillar-supported by tree branches rather than beams, and lined with white fabric for walls and floors, the compund houses two families. The goats and chickens make their names on the dirt floors. Upstairs, a makonde sits starkly empty, while below, young cousins Hassan Mansur, second from left, and Suluman Manja, right, smile with their cousins Mourahim Tarone and Assyl Mansur. The kids played games like “Dash for Treasure,” a blend of soccer and Minesweeper, and trick-or-treating in which children traded candy for cash. But capping off the event was the Great Escape, three days of monetary deprivation.
